[2]
Date: Mon, 5 Jul 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Associated Press [edited]
<http://www.phillyburbs.com/pb-dyn/news/94-07052004-327017.html>

Turkmenistan says no infectious diseases
----------------------------------------
Authorities said Mon, 5 Jul 2004, that no dangerous diseases have been
detected in Turkmenistan recently, in an apparent response to recent media
reports of a plague outbreak in the country's north.
"The epidemiological situation on Turkmen territory is favorable," the
Extraordinary Anti-Epidemics Commission said in a statement. "No cases of
any dangerous diseases have been reported."
An opposition Turkmen website, Gundogar, reported in Jun 2004, citing
unspecified sources, that Turkmenistan's northern Tashauz province was hit
by a plague outbreak. It did not say how many cases had been reported
there, but said 2 were fatal.
Rumors of the plague in the north have been circulating in the Turkmen
capital, Ashgabat, for weeks and some residents have stopped buying meat
and dairy products that came from outside the city. On Fri, 2 Jul 2004,
fearing the plague may spread to its territory, neighboring Uzbek
authorities announced restrictions on the movement of people and livestock
along the Turkmen border.
